{{Infobox person | name = Svend Olufsen | image = Peter Bang og Svend Olufsen (cropped).jpg | alt = | caption = Olufsen, circa 1930 | birth_name = Svend Andreas Grøn Olufsen | birth_date = {{Birth date|1897|12|12|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Struer, Denmark|Quistrup at Struer, Denmark]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1949|12|22|1897|12|12|df=y}} | death_place = [[Skive, Denmark]] | nationality = Danish | other_names = | known_for = [[Bang & Olufsen]] | occupation = Electrical engineer }}
'''Svend Olufsen''' was a Danish [[electrical engineer]] who co-founded [[Bang & Olufsen]] with [[:da:Peter Bang (ingeniør)|Peter Bang]]. Like Bang, Olufsen studied at the Technical University of Aarhus. Olufsen and Bang both shared an enthusiasm for radio, which at the time was in its infancy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Svend Andreas Grøn Olufsen|url=http://www.gravsted.dk/person.php?navn=svendolufsen|accessdate=28 December 2011}}</ref>
After Bang returned from a trip to the United States, he and Olufsen began running experiments in Olufsen's family manor, Quistrop, in [[Struer, Denmark]]. Their company, Bang & Olufsen, was formally established on 17 November 1925, with Olufsen primarily focusing on the business aspects.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bang & Olufsen – A Short History – The First 25 Years|url=http://www.beoworld.org/article_view.asp?id=30|work=BeoWorld: Everything Bang & Olufsen|accessdate=28 December 2011}}</ref> Olufsen's mother, Anna, helped fund the company through the sale of their family's eggs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Svend Andreas Grøn Olufsen|url=http://www.gravsted.dk/person.php?navn=svendolufsen|accessdate=28 December 2011}}</ref> Their first commercially viable product came in 1927 with the production of a radio that could connect to [[alternating current]], rather than be battery-powered.
